{{recipe}}
'''Maghrebi Charoset''' is a dried fruit and nut based paste served during the Jewish celebration of Passover by Jews from Northwest Africa.
{{see also|Cookbook:Charoset}}
==Ingredients== * 1½ [[Cookbook:Cup|C]] white [[cookbook:raisin|raisins]] * ½ C dried [[cookbook:apricot|apricots]] or dried [[cookbook:peach|peaches]], chopped * juice of two [[cookbook:orange|oranges]] * ¼ C chopped [[cookbook:almond|almonds]] * 1 [[Cookbook:Teaspoon|tsp]]. [[cookbook:cinnamon|cinnamon]] * 1 tsp. [[cookbook:ginger|ginger]], preferably freshly grated * 2 [[Cookbook:Tablespoon|T]] [[cookbook:honey|honey]] * 2 T [[cookbook:Matsoh Meal|matsoh meal]]
== Procedure == # Plump dried fruit in juice. # Mash reconstituted fruit with almond and spices to get a mortar-like texture. # Adjust texture with matsoh meal and if needed, sweeten with honey. # Serve as part of the [[Cookbook:Seder|Seder]]. The north west African tradition uses bitter greens such as endive rather than horseradish with the Charoseth.
